<p>Choosing the right scale for an architectural model depends on the model's purpose, the level of detail required, and the actual dimensions of the real object. The guidelines below are useful rules of thumb, but every project deserves its own evaluation.</p>
<h2>Start by calculating the model's size</h2>
<p>Before selecting a scale, work out how large the finished model will physically be. A model that becomes unusually tall, sprawling, or tiny is a clear sign the scale needs adjusting. The goal is a piece that's comfortable to view at arm's length and easy to move and display.</p>
<h2>Common scales — and what each is for</h2>
<p>These ranges cover the majority of architectural work. Actual dimensions always override these guidelines.</p>
<div class="spec-table">
  <div class="r"><span class="l">Interiors, units, hotel rooms</span><span class="v">1:50</span></div>
  <div class="r"><span class="l">Building architecture</span><span class="v">1:100</span></div>
  <div class="r"><span class="l">Mixed-use blocks, TODs</span><span class="v">1:200</span></div>
  <div class="r"><span class="l">Masterplans, large sites</span><span class="v">1:500</span></div>
  <div class="r"><span class="l">City-scale overview</span><span class="v">1:1000</span></div>
</div>
<h2>How we recommend a scale</h2>
<p>When we review a project, scale selection is guided by a few practical factors:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Purpose</strong> — what decision the model needs to support, from concept massing to a sales-gallery centerpiece.</li>
<li><strong>Level of detail</strong> — finer façade, glazing, and landscaping detail reads better at a larger scale.</li>
<li><strong>Viewing distance</strong> — a model seen across a gallery has different needs than one studied around a table.</li>
<li><strong>Real dimensions</strong> — the size of the building or site ultimately sets the practical bounds.</li>
</ul>
<div class="callout">The right scale ensures clarity, practicality, and visual impact. If you're unsure, send us your dimensions and intended use — we'll recommend a scale during review.</div>
